\f0\fs28 \cf0 Scrivener\'92s Snapshots feature keeps older versions of your documents around for reference. To capture a version before embarking on a major edit of a document, select 
\f1\fs24 \cf2 <$Scr_Cs::0>
\f2\b Take Snapshot 
\f1\b0 \cf0 <!$Scr_Cs::0>
\f0\fs28 (
\f1\fs24 \cf2 <$Scr_Cs::0>
\f2\b Cmd-5
\f1\b0 \cf0 <!$Scr_Cs::0>
\f0\fs28 ) in the 
\f1\fs24 \cf2 <$Scr_Cs::0>
\f2\b Documents > Snapshots
\f1\b0 \cf0 <!$Scr_Cs::0>
\f0\fs28  menu. Try that now (you will hear the sound of a camera shutter which indicates that the snapshot has been taken).\
Once you have taken a snapshot, you can edit your document safe in the knowledge that you can return to the older version whenever you want.\
Click on the \'93Snapshots\'94 button (the one with the picture of a camera on it) in the inspector header bar to see what I mean.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\li720\fi-720\sl264\slmult1\sa360\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\ls1\ilvl0\cf0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}The inspector now shows a list of snapshots at the top, which should consist of the one you took and one I took while writing the first version of this tutorial way back in 2006.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}Clicking on a snapshot in the list reveals its text in the lower part of the inspector.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}Restore an older version of your text by selecting the version you want from the list and clicking on 
\f1\fs24 \cf2 <$Scr_Cs::0>
\f2\b Roll Back
\f1\b0 \cf0 <!$Scr_Cs::0>
\f0\fs28  at the top (at which point, you will be given the option of taking another snapshot of your current version).\

